ion and posttraumatic stress disorder, in order to help develop and refine ways to treat people suffering from those conditions within the NHS. Our basic science studies use a range of techniques such as brain imaging, genetics, psychological experimentation and so on, and we use this as a platform to devise clinical strategies to use during psychological therapy. These clinical approaches are then tested in clinical treatment trials.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>This programme (see http://www.mrc-cbu.cam.ac.uk/research/emotion/cemhp/) comprises translational research into understanding and treating emotional disorders (in particular, major depressive disorder and post-traumatic stress disorder) across the lifespan. Basic science studies using neuroimaging, experimental psychology, psychophysiology, and behavioural genetics are used to trace the profiles of biased and impaired processing associated with these syndromes, within a transdiagnostic framework. Clinical proof-of-principal research translates these findings into putative therapeutic products, which are then tested in formal clinical trials under the umbrella of the Cambridge Centre for Affective Disorders (http://c2ad.mrc-cbu.cam.ac.uk/). The aim is to understand and refine existing clinical assessments and interventions and to develop novel versions thereof for dissemination within the NHS.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2017-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>0</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:p